Mitchell Myhre Manager, Regulatory Relations and Policy Interstate Power & Light Company 4902 Biltmore Lane Madison, WI 53707

General Terms and Conditions
Section 1 Definitions
A. Applicable Laws shall mean all applicable federal, state and local laws, ordinances, rules, regulations, orders, decrees or other duly authorized actions of any Governmental Authority having jurisdiction over the parties, the Transporters distribution facilities and/or the transactions under any service agreement for firm interstate transportation service.
B. Btu shall mean British Thermal Unit and, where appropriate, the plural thereof.
C. Daily Transportation Quantity shall mean the quantity of Gas that Shipper nominates for delivery from the Receipt Point(s) to the Delivery Point on a particular Gas Day.
D. Dekatherm or Dth shall mean a quantity of heat equal to ten therms or one million British Thermal Units (one MMBtu).
E. Delivery Point shall mean the point specified in the Transportation Service Agreement where Transporter shall deliver Gas to Shipper and for Rate Schedule RNG, shall mean the point where the Transporter shall deliver Gas to the interstate pipeline for the Shipper.
F. FERC or Commission shall mean Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor agency.
G. Gas or Natural Gas shall mean any mixture of hydrocarbons or of hydrocarbons and non-combustible gases, in a gaseous state, that meets the quality standards contained in these general terms.
H. Governmental Authority shall mean any federal, state, local or municipal governmental body, any governmental, regulatory or administrative agency, commission, body or other authority exercising or entitled to exercise any administrative, executive, judicial, legislative, policy, regulatory or taxing authority or power; or any court or governmental tribunal.
I. Interstate Pipeline shall mean any interstate pipeline that is directly interconnected with Transporter such that it is able to deliver Gas to the Receipt Point or receive Gas at the Delivery Point.
J. IPL Retail Gas Tariff shall mean all tariffs on file with the Iowa Utilities Board (IUB) which have been filed by Interstate Power & Light Company (IPL) and accepted by the IUB and which govern the provision of Natural Gas delivery and balancing service to retail customers of IPL.
K. Maximum Daily Quantity or MDQ shall mean the maximum quantity of Gas net of fuel loss which Transporter shall be obligated to transport and deliver in the aggregate from the Receipt Point(s) and deliver through Transporters distribution facilities to the Delivery Point.
L. MMBtu shall mean one million British Thermal Units.
M. Receipt Point(s) shall mean the point(s) specified in the Transportation Service Agreement where Transporter shall receive Gas from Shipper.
N. Renewable Gas shall mean Gas produced from organic waste that has the characteristics: (i) consistent with the provisions of all Transporter Gas standards, and (ii) that in the sole view of Transporter does not otherwise pose a hazard to inclusion in the Transporters distribution lines when comingled with Natural Gas.
O. Shipper shall mean any entity entering into a Transportation Service Agreement with Transporter to receive service in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth herein, or its successors or assigns.
P. Transportation Service Agreement shall mean any contract of Transporter providing transportation service to a Shipper.
Q. Transporter shall mean Interstate Power & Light Company, its successors or assigns.
Any defined terms used herein but not defined shall have the meanings set forth in the IPL Retail Gas Tariff.
Section 2 Applicability
A. Transporter shall provide firm interstate transportation service in accordance with these General Terms and Conditions and under the applicable rate schedule by receiving Daily Transportation Quantities delivered by Shipper to the Receipt Point(s) and by redelivering such quantities, pursuant to the terms and conditions herein and as specified in the Transportation Service Agreement, to the Delivery Point.
Section 3 Statement of Rates and Charges
A. The maximum transportation charge for transportation service shall be the maximum rate approved by the FERC for transportation under the blanket certificate issued by the FERC, and as shown in the applicable rate schedule.
B. Transporters maximum rate for transportation service shall be determined pursuant to Section 284.123(b)(1)(ii) of FERCs regulations. Transporter reserves the right to file for a higher maximum rate at any time and the maximum rate which Shipper agrees to pay shall be revised to equal such higher maximum.
C. Lost and Unaccounted For Gas. The quantity of transportation Gas received from the Shipper will be reduced by a fixed percentage, which shall represent compensation for Transporter-used Gas and Lost and Unaccounted For Gas. Such fixed percentage may be separately established by the Transporter for each of the Transporters distribution systems, or parts thereof, and shall be set forth in the Contract. This percentage may be adjusted by the Transporter from time to time.
Section 4 Gas Deliveries A. The Maximum Daily Quantity (MDQ) of Gas that Transporter shall be obligated to transport and deliver on behalf of Shipper, on a firm basis, shall be as set forth in the Transportation Service Agreement, measured at the Delivery Point(s) or Receipt Point(s) for Rate Schedule RNG. The MDQ shall not exceed the Shippers entitlement on the Interstate Pipeline at the Receipt Point(s) or Delivery Point(s), as applicable.
B. Daily Transportation Quantity Nominations. Shipper shall conform to the nomination and confirmation deadlines of Interstate Pipeline. Transporter shall not be required to accept Intra-day 2 nomination changes requested by Shipper. Upon receiving nominations, and conditioned upon acceptance and confirmation of such nominations by Interstate Pipeline, Transporter shall receive such quantities at the Receipt Point(s) and redeliver such quantities to Shipper at the Delivery Point. Daily Transportation Quantity nominations shall be considered first through the meter at the Receipt Point(s).
C. Upstream Interstate Pipeline Transportation. It shall be Shippers responsibility to arrange with the Interstate Pipeline for the delivery of Shippers Gas to the Receipt Point(s) or for the receipt of Shippers Gas at the Delivery Point(s). Shipper shall be responsible for any Interstate Pipeline imbalance charges, penalties, or other applicable charges incurred by, or applicable to, Shipper.
D. Gas Quality Specifications. Shipper shall meet the quality specifications required by the Interstate Pipeline or otherwise set forth in the Transportation Service Agreement.
Section 5 Billing and Payment
A. Billing. Transporter shall render invoices for service rendered to Shipper by the fifteenth day of each month. Such invoices shall include a statement showing the amount due applicable to the preceding month, along with a computation of the amount due and payable. When information necessary for billing purposes is in the control of Shipper, Shipper shall furnish such information to Transporter on or before the third day of the month. Both Transporter and Shipper have the right to examine at reasonable times upon prior notice and at its own expense, books, records and charts of the other to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, charge or computation made under or pursuant to any of the provisions hereof.
B. Payment. Shipper shall pay all invoices rendered for service within ten days of receiving the statement from the Transporter. Payments by Shipper to Transporter shall be made in the form of wire transfer in immediately available funds directed to a bank account designated by Transporters Controller, unless otherwise agreed. If payment differs from the invoiced amount, remittance detail should be provided with the payment within two Business Days of the payment due date. Interest on the unpaid portion of the bill shall accrue at the current rate as set forth in Section 154.501(d) of the Commissions rules and regulations, from the due date until the date of payment. If such failure to pay continues for thirty days after payment is due, Transporter, in addition to any other remedy it may have hereunder, may suspend further delivery of Gas until such amount is paid.
C. Billing Disputes. If Shipper in good faith disputes the amount of any such bill or part thereof and pays to Transporter such amounts, if any, it concedes to be correct and, at any time thereafter within thirty days of a demand made by Transporter, furnishes a good and sufficient surety bond in an amount and with surety satisfactory to Transporter or other assurance acceptable to Transporter, guaranteeing payment to Transporter of the unpaid amount, then Transporter shall not be entitled to suspend further delivery of such Gas unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond.
D. Error Adjustments. In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within thirty days of the determination thereof, provided that claim therefore shall have been made within 30 days of discovery of such error, but in any event within six months from the date of such statement, provided, however, that the party harmed by the adjustment shall have up to three months to dispute such adjustment. The riming of billing claims and adjustments referenced in the previous shall not apply in the case of deliberate omission or misrepresentation or mutual mistake of fact. Parties other statutory or contractual rights shall not be diminished by this standard. If parties are unable to agree on the adjustment of any claimed error, any resort by either of the parties to legal proceedings shall be commenced within 15 months after the supposed cause of action is alleged to have arisen, or shall thereafter be forever barred.
E. Final invoices and payments. All invoices and payments, other than those related to Taxes, shall be final unless questioned within twelve months from the date of such invoice or payment. Any error discovered as a result of a timely claim shall be adjusted within thirty days of the determination of such errors.
F. Taxes. Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for all taxes that may be levied upon and/or paid by Transporter with respect to the service performed under this Statement of Operating Conditions. Shipper shall be responsible for establishing any exemption from taxes and shall provide satisfactory evidence of such exemption to Transporter.
Section 6 Measurement and Metering
A. Measurement at Delivery Point(s). Transporter shall install meters at Delivery Point(s) or Receipt Point(s) for Rate Schedule RNG as necessary to accurately and reliably measure volumes of Gas delivered to Shipper in accordance with generally accepted industry practices. If the use of electronic or other types of flow computers is utilized, they shall be installed, and volumes shall be calculated, in accordance with generally accepted industry practices. Shipper may install, maintain, and operate at its own expense, such check measuring equipment as it desires, provided that such equipment shall be so installed so as not to interfere with the operation of Transporters facilities, including measuring equipment.
B. Metering. Transporter shall make available to Shipper isolated secure connection points from Transporters metering equipment for Shipper, at Shippers sole expense, to receive electronic signals providing pressure, flow rates, and total usage. Transporter shall also provide Shipper, on a commercially reasonable basis, a daily usage report showing actual deliveries of Gas to the Delivery Point or Receipt Point for Rate Schedule RNG. Such daily usage reports shall reflect a one-day calendar lag in information due to the download of metering information to report. If there are any differences between the daily usage report made available each day and the daily metered usage downloaded at the completion of the monthly billing period, Shipper and Transporter will accept the latter information as the usage information that will govern as to monthly billing information.
Section 7 Force Majeure
A. The term Force Majeure shall mean any unforeseeable cause beyond the reasonable control of the party claiming Force Majeure, which by exercise of due foresight such party could not reasonably have been expected to avoid and which, by the exercise of due diligence, it is unable to overcome, including, but not limited to: acts of God; acts of a public enemy; expropriation or confiscation of facilities; acts of declared or undeclared war; acts of terrorism; public disorder; rebellion or sabotage; revolution; epidemic; landslide; lightning; fire; hurricane; earthquake; flood; riot; explosion; partial or entire failure of utilities; breakage or accident to Gas transportation or distribution facilities or equipment or lines of pipe; freezing of wells or pipelines; strikes; work stoppage associated with labor dispute; injunction or quarantine; changes in Applicable Laws subsequent to the Effective Date hereof; or action or inaction by any Governmental Authority.
B. Except for Shippers obligation to make payments as may be included under a Transportation Service Agreement, the parties shall be excused from performing their respective obligations under such Transportation Service Agreement and shall not be liable in damages or otherwise if and to the extent that they are unable to so perform or are prevented from performing by Force Majeure, provided that:
(1) the non-performing party, as promptly as practicable after the occurrence of the Force Majeure, gives the other party written notice describing the particulars of the occurrence; in the event the Force Majeure outage would cause Transporter to be unable to transport supply for the current or next Gas Day, Transporter will notify Shipper by phone as soon as practicable;
(2) the suspension of performance is of no greater scope and of no greater duration than is reasonably required by the Force Majeure;
(3) the non-performing party uses all reasonable efforts to remedy its inability to perform; and,
(4) as soon as the non-performing party is able to resume performance of its obligations hereunder, it give prompt written notice thereof to the other party.
Section 8 Curtailment
A. To the extent that Transporters facilities are unable on any Gas Day, by reason of Force Majeure or otherwise, to provide delivery to meet Shippers Daily Transportation Quantity, Transporters interruptible customers shall first be curtailed. After all of Transporters interruptible customers have been curtailed, Shippers Daily Transportation Quantity shall, if necessary, be curtailed on a pro rata basis with Transporters other firm obligations at the affected Receipt Point(s).
Section 9 Creditworthiness
A. Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue to perform service on behalf of any Shipper (i) that has applied for bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, (ii) that fails to make prompt and full payment to Transporter when due for transportation and balancing services rendered by Transporter, or (iii) for which Transporter has reasonable grounds for insecurity as to Shippers performance of its obligations under any transaction governed hereby. If any event set forth in (i), (ii) or (iii) shall occur, in addition to any other rights or remedies available to Transporter, it may in writing demand adequate assurance of due performance and until it receives such assurance, may suspend any performance for which it has not already been paid.
B. Adequate assurance of performance of the type described in A. above shall include (i) posting of a letter of credit in form and from a financial institution acceptable to Transporter in an amount equal to three months of transportation charges; (ii) cash prepayment in an amount equal to three months of transportation charges; or (iii) delivery of other forms of security acceptable to the Transporter in an amount equal to three months of demand charges. Shippers failure to deliver adequate assurance properly demanded within two business days of receiving Transporters demand therefore shall constitute a breach of the applicable transportation transaction, entitling Transporter to (i) terminate any or all transportation transactions with Shipper, (ii) liquidate Gas balances in Transporters possession and applying the resulting funds to the payment of all amounts owed and that become owed for services under any transportation transactions governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions, and (iii) seek all other remedies available for breach for all applicable transportation transactions.
Section 10 New Facilities
A. Transporter shall not be required to provide any requested transportation service that would require construction or acquisition by Transporter of any new facilities or expansion of Transporters existing facilities. Transporter, in its discretion, and subject to regulatory approvals, may agree to construct or acquire new facilities, or expand existing facilities, to provide service requested by any Shipper. In such event, Shipper agrees to reimburse Transporter for the total incremental cost of the new facilities or expansion of existing facilities, unless otherwise mutually agreed in writing. Transporter shall determine method of reimbursement, either lump sum, installment, or as-used.
B. To the extent Transporter agrees to construct or acquire any new facilities or expand existing facilities, any such facilities shall be contracted, maintained, owned and operated by Transporter, except as may be mutually agreed in writing. The design and installation of all facilities shall be in accordance with the specifications determined by Transporter in its reasonable discretion.
Section 11 Balancing Service Shipper and Transporter shall make arrangements for the balancing of receipts and deliveries, including any arrangements to accommodate imbalances between Shipper and Interstate Pipeline. Unless otherwise agreed-to between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper shall be obligated to balance on a daily basis the receipt of Shipper-Owned Gas by Transporter at Shippers Receipt Point(s) with deliveries of such Gas by Transporter to Shippers Delivery Point, subject to restrictions and conditions of Transporters interstate pipeline and subject to the conditions of this Statement of Operating Conditions. Shipper is responsible for keeping informed as to the daily volume of deliveries by Transporter to Shipper of Shipper-owned Gas so as to enable the Shipper to adjust its shipments of Shipper-owned Gas by its supplier of Gas to Transporter to ensure that receipts and deliveries of Gas into and out of Transporters system will be in balance. On a monthly basis, Transporter will provide a statement to Shipper, that will show imbalances resulting from the over- or under-delivery of Gas, adjusted for losses.
A. Daily Balancing. Overage (positive) imbalance quantities (receipts by Transporter of Shipper-owned Gas, adjusted for losses greater than deliveries to Shipper) and underage (negative) imbalance quantities (receipts by Transporter of Shipper-owned Gas, adjusted for losses, less than deliveries to Shipper) will be subject to the following charges. Percentage tolerances shown below are based on Transporters receipts of Shipper-owned Gas:
(a) Non-Constraint Day Overage and Underage Balancing Charges: A Non- Constraint Day shall mean any day other than a High Flow or Low Flow Constraint Day.
Tolerance Charges
0 to +/- 10% No Charge +/- 10% up to +/- 20% $0.25 per Dth +/- 20% up to +/- 30% $0.50 per Dth Greater than +/- 30% $1.00 per Dth
(b) High Flow Constraint Day Overage and Underage Balancing Charges: A High Flow Constraint Day shall be defined as any day on which curtailment or interruption may be required or Transporters uses due to constraints declared by Transporters interstate pipeline or constraints on Transporters distribution system. Transporter shall notify Shipper of a High Flow Constraint Day and make every effort to give Shipper at least two (2) hours notice of a High Flow Constraint Day. Tolerance Charges
0 to -3% $0.50 per Dth Greater than -3% The higher of $10.00 per Dth or the actual pipeline penalties incurred 0 to +30% No Charge Greater than +30% $1.00 per Dth
(c) Low Flow Constraint Day Overage and Underage Balancing Charges: A Low Flow Constraint Day shall be defined as any day on which Transporters interstate pipeline curtail the receipt of Gas when such interstate pipeline experience over deliveries of Gas into their system affecting the operating integrity of their system or constraints on Transporters distribution system. Transporter shall notify Shipper of a Low Flow Constraint Day and make every effort to give Shipper at least two (2) hours notice of a Low Flow Constraint Day.
Tolerance Charges 0 to +3% $0.10 per Dth Greater than +3% $5.00 per Dth 0 to -30% No Charge Greater than -30% $1.00 per Dth
B. Monthly Balancing Charges.
(a) Overdeliveries: In addition to the above daily balancing charges, daily overage imbalances (receipt by Transporter of Shipper-owned Gas greater than deliveries by Transporter to Shipper) will be deemed to have been sold to Transporter at a rate equal to the Gas Daily Index Price per dekatherm for the Chicago City-Gate GDD, less $0.08 (with the exception of shippers that transport on the Northern Natural Gas Pipeline or the Northern Border Pipeline into Mason City or Marshalltown, in which case the NNG Ventura City daily delivered price per dekatherm plus $0.04 will be used as the index price). The payment for such excess Gas sold to Transporter shall be credited to the Shippers monthly bill.
(b) Underdeliveries: In addition to the above daily balancing charges, daily underage imbalances will be deemed as Overrun Gas. It is the Gas taken from the Transporter without backup service and for which prior nominations and arrangements have not been made. The rate for Overrun Gas shall be the Gas Daily Index Price per dekatherm for the Chicago City-Gate GDD, plus $0.08 (with the exception of shippers that transport on the Northern Natural Gas Pipeline or the Northern Border Pipeline into Mason City or Marshalltown, in which case the NNG Ventura City daily delivered price per dekatherm plus $0.20 will be used as the index price). If Transporter incurs incremental costs to secure Gas for the Shipper, including any demand charges or penalties, over and above the penalty charges listed above, such incremental costs would be charged to Shipper.
C. Group Balancing Service. a) The Shipper shall have the option to choose a group balancing service. By selecting this option, a defined group of shippers shall be treated as one customer for the balancing terms of this Statement of Operating Conditions. This group of shippers shall be defined as a Shipper Pool. In all other respect, the Shipper shall operate individually under the provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
b) The term Shipper Pool Agent shall mean the person, corporation, partnership, or other legal entity that acts on behalf of the Shipper Pool. The Shipper Pool Agent shall enter into a group balancing service agreement with Transporter which shall be for a term of not less than six months. The Transporter may act as the Shipper Pool Agent, based upon terms and conditions agreeable to Transporter and the Shipper Pool.
Applicability: a. The Shipper Pool Agent must notify Transporter of the delivery point(s) to be grouped at least one (1) working day prior to the date for beginning of the month nominations. b. The Shipper Pool Agent will provide the Transporter with individual delivery point daily nominations. Each delivery point or receipt point for Rate Schedule RNG within the pool must have operational telemetering in place. c. The Shipper Pool Agent shall be responsible for pipeline imbalances, penalties, overrun Gas charges or other charges it may create with the pipeline supplier. d. All balancing charges or balancing-related obligations of the Shipper Pool shall be the responsibility of the Shipper Pool Agent. Should the Shipper Pool Agent fail to satisfy such obligation, the individual customers in the Shipper Pool shall remain responsible for such obligations. e. If the Shipper Pool and/or the Shipper Pool Agent do not comply with the provisions of the applicable group balancing service agreement, Transporter may terminate the group balancing service agreement and each shipper whose delivery point is part of the Shipper Pool will be individually responsible for the settlement of Gas transportation imbalances and other charges regardless of payments that the shipper may have rendered to the Shipper Pool Agent. f. Transporter reserves the right to terminate the group balancing service agreement upon three (3) days written notice. However, Transporter will notify the shipper of the problems and allow the Shipper Pool Agent five (5) working days to correct them before such written notice to terminate is issued. g. In the event the group balancing service agreement is terminated during any month, all shippers with a delivery point within the shipper pool shall be billed separately for any imbalances incurred during that month.
Statement of Effective Interstate Service Rates
Rate Schedule FT
Availability: Shippers who use Transporters distribution system to carry or transport Shipper-owned Gas to the Shippers premises. Such Gas may be directly purchased under separate contract from producers, pipeline companies or other third parties. Delivery shall be through one meter, at one point, and where such premises are adjacent to an existing Gas main of adequate capacity.
Rate: I. Customer Charge: Maximum requirement - Less than 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Small Volume (Non-Residential General Service): $1.11769 per day Maximum requirement - Over 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Large Volume (Large General Service) and Large Volume Transportation Demand- Commodity: $7.39645 per day The Shipper shall be responsible for all costs associated with any specific plant such as telemetering required in providing contract carriage service to Shipper
II. Volumetric Charge. For volumes transported and delivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point, Shipper shall pay Transporter a volumetric charge not to exceed:
(a) $2.0886/Dth if Shippers highest single day volume during the month was less than or equal to 200 Dth; or,
(b) $0.9331/Dth if Shippers highest single day volume during the month was greater than 200 Dth per Dekatherm.
Rate Schedule RNG
Availability: Shippers that deliver Renewable Gas into the Transporters Natural Gas system (RG Transportation Customer). RG Transportation Customers electing service under this rate schedule shall pay for all equipment necessary to effectuate deliveries of Renewable Gas at the point of interconnection with the Transporter, including, but not limited to, valves, separators, telemetric equipment, quality measurement, odorant and other equipment necessary to regulate and deliver Gas at the interconnection point. Prior to commencement of this service, the RG Transportation Customer must have Transporter-installed telemetric equipment in place to monitor daily usage. The RG Transportation Customer shall pay for computer programming changes, if any, required to add the RG Transportation Customers new interconnection point and any billing system changes required. Such payments shall be considered nonrefundable contributions. Character of Service: The RG Transportation Customer and Transporter shall enter into a mutually agreeable written contract to define the specific terms of service under this rate schedule. All equipment installed shall remain the sole property of the Transporter unless otherwise stated in the contract. During a Critical Day or Operational Flow Order, the Transporter will have the right to restrict the availability of deliveries and receipts made under this rate schedule. In the event a restriction occurs, a Transporter representative will notify the RG Transportation Customer at such time. The RG Transportation Customer shall be responsible for ensuring that Renewable Gas delivered to the Transporter meets all Transporter Gas quality standards. Service under this rate schedule is interruptible, and the receipt and delivery of Renewable Gas is subject to curtailment. RG Transportation Customer agrees to curtail receipts and deliveries of Renewable Gas to the Points of Receipt and Delivery to the extent and for the periods requested by the Transporter. Service under this rate schedule is dependent on (a) the Transporters ability to physically accept Renewable Gas deliveries at the designated Receipt Point on a particular day; (b) the ability of the interconnecting pipeline to receive the total quantities produced; and (c) the Renewable Gas meeting all applicable Gas quality standards. Rate: I. Customer Charge: Maximum requirement - Less than 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Small Volume (Non-Residential General Service): $1.11769 per day Maximum requirement - Over 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Large Volume (Large General Service) and Large Volume Transportation Demand- Commodity: $7.39645 per day II. Demand Charge: $8.46391 per Dekatherm of Daily Contract Demand. Applicable to Large Volume Transportation Demand-Commodity Customers as an optional rate. Daily Contract Demand Rate shall mean that portion of the amount to be paid monthly by the Customer for Gas Transportation Service which is based upon the Customers Contract. III. Quality Monitoring Charge: $58.3562 per day. IV. Maintenance Charge: $13.6986 per day. V. Commodity Charge: Maximum requirement - Less than 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Small Volume (Non-Residential General Service): $0.20866/Thm Maximum requirement - Over 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Large Volume (Large General Service): $0.09331/Thm Maximum requirement - Over 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Large Volume Transportation Demand-Commodity, as an optional rate: $0.03633 per therm VI. Odorization Charge: Maximum requirement - Less than 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Small Volume (Non-Residential General Service): $0.0014 per therm Maximum requirement - Over 200 Dth/day or 6,000 Dth/month Large Volume (Large General Service) and Large Volume Transportation Demand-Commodity: $0.0003 per therm
Retention Percentage: Per the terms of the Transportation Service Agreement
